@node Introduction "WaitSignal Documentation - Introduction"

If you've never edited shell scripts, you'll propably won't need this program.

@{b}WaitSignal@{ub} is a little helper program for better realisation of  shell  scripts.
It  has  only one purpose - waiting for a specified signal (you can send signals
with the BREAK command). This enables you to do multitasking synchronization  of
more or less independet processes.

While writing some nice shell  scripts  I've  been  searching  for  a  symmetric
command  to  BREAK.  But  there  was only WAIT, and WAIT was only able to wait a
period of time and being breaked by the CTRL-C signal. Unfortunately the  CTRL-C
signal was sent to the parent process, too, and everything got aborted.

With @{b}WaitSignal@{ub} I've been able to  do  simple  multitasking  synchronization  in
shell  scripts.  A  background process was launched in it's own shell window and
the foreground process was waiting for the  signal  of  the  background  process
saying that it has finished.

@{b}WaitSignal@{ub} is able to wait for any AmigaDOS signal like CTRL-C, -D, -E, -F. Even
combinations are permitted.

Created using SAS/C 6.58.

@endnode
 
@node Usage "WaitSignal Documentation - Usage"

@{b}WaitSignal@{ub} can only be used from the Shell.
  
These are all command line arguments understood by @{b}WaitSignal@{ub}:

@{b}· ALL/S@{ub} - wait for all signals at once
@{b}· C/S@{ub} - wait for the CTRL-C (abort process) signal
@{b}· D/S@{ub} - wait for the CTRL-D (abort script) signal
@{b}· E/S@{ub} - wait for the CTRL-E signal
@{b}· F/S@{ub} - wait for the CTRL-F (window to fron) signal

If no signal has  been  specified,  CTRL-C  is  being  waited  for  by  default.
Otherwise WaitSignal would wait forever.

I prefer the CTRL-E and CTRL-F signals, since they don't try to  break  anything
and are just for communication purposes. CTRL-C and CTRL-D could stop your
shell script you're running WaitSignal in as well.


@{u}Examples:@{uu}

1> WaitSignal C F
   - wait for signal CTRL-C or CTRL-F being raised

Another nice example can be found in the @{i}Examples@{ui} directory.

@endnode

